Content: I'm just really upset today and I had to troll... no, I'm fine, and I wrote that post sincerely. Author: earthboundkid
Content:
> The only thing that seems to work for me is to make whatever I'm working on significantly more fun than what I should be doing.

That's very true. Having two or more tasks at hand is always key, so that you can do the least intimidating of the two. The downside to this approach is that sometimes you really do need to do the more intimidating one.

Author: ardit33
Content:
This is an old speach, but a good one. It is crazy on how on every city, the oldest parts (the one build before the 30s) are actually design well, human scale, and apealing.Most things built after the 40ss, is this very ugly strip mall design, that is soul drenching, depressing and plain ugly. You can put as many palm trees as you want, it is still like putting a lipstick on a fat pig.

Take example: San Francisco, built mostly before 1920, and then SJ, or most of the peninsula, build mostly after the 50s.\nWhich tourists ever say, I came here to see San Jose?

Even when I visited Kansas City, the oldest part has some good charm and apeal, and some character. As soon as you drove out of the oldest parts, you end up with this insane grid of streets and strip malls.

Author: scorxn
Content: Though I find this comment a bit trollish, I have to ask, which parts do you disagree with? For my own two cents, I grew up in Metro Detroit, which largely resembles the concrete wasteland Kunstler criticizes. And the most accessible, generally enjoyable place I've inhabited was The Loop in St. Louis -- a well-defined, fairly small example of "a place worth caring about."

Author: anr
Content:
Knuth's TAOCP, Vol I (page 79 on the 3rd edition) has a very nice introduction to Fibonacci numbers.

The article doesn't mention the classical problem proposed by Fibonacci: "How many rabbits can be produced from a single pair in a year's time?"

(each pair produces a new pair of offspring every month, each new pair becomes fertile at the age of one month).
